  "opinion": "As a retired man from Bologna who spent his life in manual trades and never went beyond a vocational diploma, I’ve seen how stereotypes can quietly harm people. Stereotype threat in STEM isn’t just a theory—it’s something that happens when someone feels their identity might be judged as less capable in a field like engineering or physics. My own children, who went to university, sometimes told me they felt pressure because they were the only ones in their class who weren’t ‘typical’ students. It’s a subtle but heavy burden. I’ve never been exposed to the complex academic jargon that explains this phenomenon, but I’ve felt it in my own life—when I’d try to fix a broken appliance and my hands felt clumsy because I’d been told, ‘You’re not a mechanic.’ That fear of being labeled can make people give up before they even start. Should we address it? Absolutely. But not with big lectures or programs that don’t reach the people who need it most. In my community, where people talk over bread and coffee, we need to start by listening. If a young person feels like they don’t belong in STEM, we should ask why, not assume it’s their fault. Maybe it’s because they were told they’re not smart enough to handle math. We can help by showing them that everyone can learn, just like how I learned to bake bread from scratch. Addressing stereotype threat means changing the way we talk about skills and talents, not with words that sound like they’re from a textbook but with real-life examples that make people feel included. In my quiet life, I’ve seen that small gestures—like helping someone understand a problem without judgment—can make a big difference. It’s about building trust, not just fixing numbers.",
